ords/7558933/access/grants", "access_links": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/access/links", "access_request": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/access/request", "access_users": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/access/users", "archive": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/files-archive", "archive_media": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/media-files-archive", "communities": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/communities", "communities-suggestions": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/communities-suggestions", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7558933", "draft": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/draft", "file_modification": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/file-modification", "files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/files", "latest": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/versions/latest", "latest_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/7558933/latest", "media_files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/media-files", "parent": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558932", "parent_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7558932", "parent_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.7558932", "parent_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/7558932", "preview_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/7558933?preview=1", "request_deletion": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/request-deletion", "requests": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/requests", "reserve_doi": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/draft/pids/doi", "self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933", "self_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7558933", "self_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.7558933", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/7558933", "self_iiif_manifest": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:7558933/manifest", "self_iiif_sequence": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:7558933/sequence/default", "versions": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/7558933/versions"}, "media_files": {"count": 0, "enabled": false, "entries": {}, "order": [], "total_bytes": 0}, "metadata": {"creators": [{"affiliations": [{"name": "Hanover College"}], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Van Iten", "given_name": "H.", "name": "Van Iten, H.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [{"name": "University of California - Riverside"}], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Hughes", "given_name": "Nigel C.", "identifiers": [{"identifier": "0000-0001-9671-5569", "scheme": "orcid"}], "name": "Hughes, Nigel C.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [{"name": "University of California - Riverside"}], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "John", "given_name": "D.L.", "name": "John, D.L.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [{"name": "Pomona College"}], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Gaines", "given_name": "Robert R.", "name": "Gaines, Robert R.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [{"name": "University of Texas - Austin"}], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Colbert", "given_name": "M.W.", "name": "Colbert, M.W.", "type": "personal"}}], "description": "\u003cp\u003eTwo specimens of \u003cem\u003eMetaconularia manni\u003c/em\u003e (Roy) from the lower Middle Silurian Scotch Grove Formation (eastern Iowa) exhibit well-defined, relict soft parts replicated in silica. \u0026nbsp;One of these specimens bears phosphatic periderm, while the other specimen is a mold.\u0026nbsp; Present within the erect, undistorted apical region of the specimen preserving periderm, on opposite sides of the peridermal cavity, are two small, elongate masses of silica located near the midlines of two of the four faces.\u0026nbsp; Present in the central portion of the other specimen, at a somewhat greater distance from the apex, are five pairs of hollow, elongate, keeled-pouch-like bodies (pouches), the long axes of which converge on the center of the fossil.\u0026nbsp; Each pair of pouches is associated with a short, narrow, gently curved or broadly u-shaped tube, also composed of silica.\u0026nbsp; Additionally, two of the pouch/tube combinations are associated with a pair of rectilinear furrows that correspond to the paired internal carinae that straddled the conulariid\u0026rsquo;s facial midlines. \u0026nbsp;We interpret the paired pouches and short tubes in the moldic specimen as relic conulariid soft parts homologous, respectively, to the interradial gonads and retractor muscles of extant, stauromedusan and polypoid scyphozoan cnidarians.\u0026nbsp; Unlike most conulariids, which exhibit four faces, this individual had five faces, an aberrant morphology known in one other conulariid.\u0026nbsp; The two small masses in the other specimen are more difficult to interpret, but they, too, may be relic gonads or longitudinal muscles.\u0026nbsp; These interpretations imply that, as in certain extant scyphozoans, at least one conulariid lost the free-living, sexual medusoid life phase.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis file is a rendered CT scan of the silicified \u0026quot;rosette\u0026quot; in UWGM 6834\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe 3-D geometry of silicified relic soft parts preserved within the specimens and partially obscured by dolomitic rock matrix was determined using ultra-high resolution (Ketcham and Carlson, 2001), 3-D scanning tomography in the University of Texas High-Resolution X-ray CT Facility (Department of Geological Sciences, Jackson School of Geosciences, The University of Texas at Austin).\u0026nbsp; The CT analysis gathered 625 slices, with a slice thickness and interslice spacing of 0.0554 mm and a field of reconstruction of 26 mm, yielding an interpixel spacing of 0.05078 mm.\u0026nbsp; The resultant 3-D model (Fig. 5) was generated using VGStudioMax.\u003c/p\u003e", "publication_date": "2023-01-22", "publisher": "Zenodo", "resource_type": {"id": "publication-article", "title": {"de": "Zeitschriftenartikel", "en": "Journal article"}}, "rights": [{"description": {"en": "The Creative Commons Attribution license allows re-distribution and re-use of a licensed work on the condition that the creator is appropriately credited."}, "icon": "cc-by-icon", "id": "cc-by-4.0", "props": {"scheme": "spdx", "url": "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode"}, "title": {"en": "Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International"}}], "subjects": [{"subject": "Cnidaria, Medusozoa, Scyphozoa, Conulariida, Silicification, Relic Soft Parts"}], "title": "Conulariid soft parts replicated in silica from the Scotch Grove Formation (lower Middle Silurian) of east-central Iowa"}, "parent": {"access": {"owned_by": {"user": "485219"}, "settings": {"accept_conditions_text": null, "allow_guest_requests": false, "allow_user_requests": false, "secret_link_expiration": 0}}, "communities": {"default": "5e858b73-9349-436b-b29a-87340670cfdf", "entries": [{"access": {"member_policy": "open", "members_visibility": "public", "record_submission_policy": "open", "review_policy": "open", "visibility": "public"}, "children": {"allow": false}, "created": "2015-10-01T19:57:16+00:00", "custom_fields": {}, "deletion_status": {"is_deleted": false, "status": "P"}, "id": "5e858b73-9349-436b-b29a-87340670cfdf", "links": {}, "metadata": {"curation_policy": "No specific policy just yet", "description": "3D datasets relating to palaeontology (or \u0027paleontology\u0027 if you prefer)", "page": "", "title": "Palaeontology 3D Data"}, "revision_id": 0, "slug": "palaeo3d", "updated": "2017-04-04T10:18:22.580672+00:00"}], "ids": ["5e858b73-9349-436b-b29a-87340670cfdf"]}, "id": "7558932", "pids": {"doi": {"client": "datacite", "identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7558932", "provider": "datacite"}}}, "pids": {"doi": {"client": "datacite", "identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7558933", "provider": "datacite"}, "oai": {"identifier": "oai:zenodo.org:7558933", "provider": "oai"}}, "revision_id": 3, "stats": {"all_versions": {"data_volume": 674591720.0, "downloads": 55, "unique_downloads": 54, "unique_views": 172, "views": 174}, "this_version": {"data_volume": 674591720.0, "downloads": 55, "unique_downloads": 54, "unique_views": 172, "views": 174}}, "status": "published", "swh": {}, "ui": {"access_status": {"description_l10n": "The record and files are publicly accessible.", "embargo_date_l10n": null, "icon": "unlock", "id": "open", "message_class": "", "title_l10n": "Open"}, "created_date_l10n_long": "January 24, 2023", "creators": {"affiliations": [[1, "Hanover College", null], [2, "University of California - Riverside", null], [3, "Pomona College", null], [4, "University of Texas - Austin", null]], "creators": [{"affiliations": [[1, "Hanover College"]], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Van Iten", "given_name": "H.", "name": "Van Iten, H.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [[2, "University of California - Riverside"]], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Hughes", "given_name": "Nigel C.", "identifiers": [{"identifier": "0000-0001-9671-5569", "scheme": "orcid"}], "name": "Hughes, Nigel C.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [[2, "University of California - Riverside"]], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "John", "given_name": "D.L.", "name": "John, D.L.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [[3, "Pomona College"]], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Gaines", "given_name": "Robert R.", "name": "Gaines, Robert R.", "type": "personal"}}, {"affiliations": [[4, "University of Texas - Austin"]], "person_or_org": {"family_name": "Colbert", "given_name": "M.W.", "name": "Colbert, M.W.", "type": "personal"}}]}, "custom_fields": {"journal:journal": {"title": "Journal of Paleonotology"}}, "description_stripped": "Two specimens of Metaconularia manni (Roy) from the lower Middle Silurian Scotch Grove Formation (eastern Iowa) exhibit well-defined, relict soft parts replicated in silica. \u00a0One of these specimens bears phosphatic periderm, while the other specimen is a mold.\u00a0 Present within the erect, undistorted apical region of the specimen preserving periderm, on opposite sides of the peridermal cavity, are two small, elongate masses of silica located near the midlines of two of the four faces.\u00a0 Present in the central portion of the other specimen, at a somewhat greater distance from the apex, are five pairs of hollow, elongate, keeled-pouch-like bodies (pouches), the long axes of which converge on the center of the fossil.\u00a0 Each pair of pouches is associated with a short, narrow, gently curved or broadly u-shaped tube, also composed of silica.\u00a0 Additionally, two of the pouch/tube combinations are associated with a pair of rectilinear furrows that correspond to the paired internal carinae that straddled the conulariid\u2019s facial midlines. \u00a0We interpret the paired pouches and short tubes in the moldic specimen as relic conulariid soft parts homologous, respectively, to the interradial gonads and retractor muscles of extant, stauromedusan and polypoid scyphozoan cnidarians.\u00a0 Unlike most conulariids, which exhibit four faces, this individual had five faces, an aberrant morphology known in one other conulariid.\u00a0 The two small masses in the other specimen are more difficult to interpret, but they, too, may be relic gonads or longitudinal muscles.\u00a0 These interpretations imply that, as in certain extant scyphozoans, at least one conulariid lost the free-living, sexual medusoid life phase.\n\n\nThis file is a rendered CT scan of the silicified \"rosette\" in UWGM 6834\n\n\nThe 3-D geometry of silicified relic soft parts preserved within the specimens and partially obscured by dolomitic rock matrix was determined using ultra-high resolution (Ketcham and Carlson, 2001), 3-D scanning tomography in the University of Texas High-Resolution X-ray CT Facility (Department of Geological Sciences, Jackson School of Geosciences, The University of Texas at Austin).\u00a0 The CT analysis gathered 625 slices, with a slice thickness and interslice spacing of 0.0554 mm and a field of reconstruction of 26 mm, yielding an interpixel spacing of 0.05078 mm.\u00a0 The resultant 3-D model (Fig. 5) was generated using VGStudioMax.", "is_draft": false, "publication_date_l10n_long": "January 22, 2023", "publication_date_l10n_medium": "Jan 22, 2023", "publishing_information": {"journal": "Journal of Paleonotology, 2023."}, "resource_type": {"id": "publication-article", "title_l10n": "Journal article"}, "rights": [{"description_l10n": "The Creative Commons Attribution license allows re-distribution and re-use of a licensed work on the condition that the creator is appropriately credited.", "icon": "cc-by-icon", "id": "cc-by-4.0", "props": {"scheme": "spdx", "url": "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode"}, "title_l10n": "Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International"}], "updated_date_l10n_long": "February 6, 2023", "version": "v1"}, "updated": "2023-02-06T10:20:49.650637+00:00", "versions": {"index": 1, "is_latest": true}}' data-preview='false'>
